    "summary": "Hans Nieuwenhuis studied law before devoting his professional life to the theater.He assisted many famous stage directors and made his directing debut with The Netherlands Opera in 1978. He staged 7 productions for this company (a.o. La Boh\u00e8me, Parsifal, Merry Wives of Windsor). His international career started in 1981 with the USA premiere of Philip Glass' Satyagraha (Brooklyn Academy of Music NYC. After that he directed more then 100 productions all over the world. He was a stage director for L\u2019Op\u00e9ra de Nice in France, The Canadian Opera Company, Manitoba Opera, L'Op\u00e9ra de Montreal, Opera Colorado, Long Beach Opera, San Francisco Opera, Hawaii Opera Theatre, Western Opera Theater, Opera Omaha, Lincoln Center New York, Pacific Opera Victoria (Canada), Bangkok Opera and other companies in Europe, Asia and North America. Recently he directed Dido and Aeneas for Opera Zuid and L\u2019Opera Royal de Walloon, followed by Mozart\u2019s Figaro for Opera Hawaii, Die Fledermaus, touring in the Netherlands and Belgium and Cosi Fan Tutte for Opera Studio Nederland. Last year he directed La Voix Humaine by Poulenc and a new production of Monteverdi's L'Incoronazione di Poppea for the Trentino Music Festival in Italy. \n\nDuring the last 30 years Mr.Nieuwenhuis has devoted a lot of his time to young opera singers: he has taught and directed for the San Francisco Opera Center, Curtis Institute in Philadelphia, Yale University and Michigan University, McGill University in Montreal, the conservatories in Utrecht, Amsterdam and Maastricht in the Netherlands, several conservatories in China, the Tchaikovsky Conservatorium in Moscow and the Studio of the New National Theatre in Tokyo. He has given Master Classes in the USA, Thailand, Russia, Germany, Croatia, Italy, France, Canada, Austria, Belgium, Japan, Ukraine and China.Mr. Nieuwenhuis was the  founder and from 1992-2011 General Director of Opera Studio Nederland. He currently works for the international Orfeo Foundation. In 2012 Mr. Nieuwenhuis was honored for his work and made a Knight in the Order of Orange Nassau by Dutch Queen Beatrix.",
